[SPEAKER_16]: Mr. President, I think we all know this is an ongoing problem.

2581
03:14:50,846 --> 03:14:53,908
[SPEAKER_16]: The biggest problem is the entrance to Rice Ponds.

2582
03:14:54,288 --> 03:14:55,889
[SPEAKER_16]: It's on a blind turn.

2583
03:14:56,650 --> 03:15:01,373
[SPEAKER_16]: So to put a crosswalk there would be very dangerous, but what it should have

2584
03:15:01,889 --> 03:15:05,190
[SPEAKER_16]: is a light further up with a push button.

2585
03:15:05,210 --> 03:15:10,411
[SPEAKER_16]: So when people want to cross, the light would stop maybe 10 to 15 yards away.

2586
03:15:10,431 --> 03:15:13,952
[SPEAKER_16]: That would stop the cars as the people are crossing.

2587
03:15:14,672 --> 03:15:23,514
[SPEAKER_16]: Or maybe we should look at at some point changing the entrance of Wright's Pawn so it's not directly on the turn.

2588
03:15:25,055 --> 03:15:28,135
[SPEAKER_16]: So when cars come down, they won't see anybody in the crosswalk.

2589
03:15:28,476 --> 03:15:29,976
[SPEAKER_16]: That's really the biggest issue there.

2590
03:15:31,926 --> 03:15:33,087
[SPEAKER_16]: Thank you, Vice President Carviello.

2591
03:15:33,627 --> 03:15:34,427
[SPEAKER_16]: Councilor Morrell.

2592
03:15:35,187 --> 03:15:35,868
[SPEAKER_31]: Thank you, Mr. President.

2593
03:15:35,888 --> 03:15:40,210
[SPEAKER_31]: Yeah, I just want to add that I thank my fellow councilors for their design ideas.

2594
03:15:40,270 --> 03:15:52,615
[SPEAKER_31]: And in talking with the traffic engineer and his areas of expertise, I understand that they're looking at the many ways they can approach this to be in compliance with certain ADA things, the sight line, all of that.

2595
03:15:53,035 --> 03:16:00,338
[SPEAKER_31]: They're definitely working on getting creative to make this a much safer crossing, whether the existing crossings,

2596
03:16:00,788 --> 03:16:02,329
[SPEAKER_31]: adding this crossing if possible.

2597
03:16:02,449 --> 03:16:07,291
[SPEAKER_31]: So I think the ideas are definitely there and to Councilor Knight's point, it's just making it happen.

2598
03:16:08,192 --> 03:16:08,652
[SPEAKER_31]: So thank you.

2599
03:16:09,232 --> 03:16:10,133
[SPEAKER_37]: Thank you, Councilor Morrell.

2600
03:16:10,553 --> 03:16:13,755
[SPEAKER_37]: Any other questions or comments from the council or councilors?

2601
03:16:17,236 --> 03:16:17,596
[SPEAKER_37]: Okay.

2602
03:16:18,337 --> 03:16:20,238
[SPEAKER_37]: Any other questions or comments from the public?

2603
03:16:21,258 --> 03:16:23,579
[SPEAKER_36]: Let's see, we have Marshall.

2604
03:16:23,599 --> 03:16:26,621
[SPEAKER_36]: Name and address for the record, please, Marshall.

2605
03:16:27,978 --> 03:16:30,019
[SPEAKER_20]: Yeah, I'm Marshall Mootenode, 33 Waterville.

2606
03:16:31,319 --> 03:16:38,421
[SPEAKER_20]: I run all the streets around the Fells, and this one is by far the scariest crossing.

2607
03:16:39,221 --> 03:16:40,482
[SPEAKER_20]: I almost got hit by a car.

2608
03:16:40,502 --> 03:16:44,483
[SPEAKER_20]: And for the longest time, I couldn't understand why.

2609
03:16:44,503 --> 03:16:48,084
[SPEAKER_20]: I couldn't get cars even to stop for me during rush hour.

2610
03:16:48,104 --> 03:16:52,405
[SPEAKER_20]: I would sometimes wave a stick out into the street, like, please stop.

2611
03:16:53,266 --> 03:16:56,287
[SPEAKER_20]: And repainting the crosswalk will not do anything.

2612
03:16:56,467 --> 03:16:57,747
[SPEAKER_20]: You cannot see the crosswalk.

2613
03:16:59,224 --> 03:17:00,685
[SPEAKER_20]: in a car as you approach it.

2614
03:17:01,885 --> 03:17:07,908
[SPEAKER_20]: I didn't realize that until I approached it in a car, finally, but you just cannot see it.

2615
03:17:08,788 --> 03:17:16,131
[SPEAKER_20]: The two signs are small, you know, there's also, there's, it's just not, I think it needs to be reimagined.

2616
03:17:19,409 --> 03:17:30,211
[SPEAKER_20]: Furthermore, I think it's, I'm really glad to hear that the traffic engineer is thinking about this comprehensively, because there are a number of confusing factors on this road.

2617
03:17:30,851 --> 03:17:42,793
[SPEAKER_20]: You have a 25 mile an hour speed limit, then a speed light thing that flashes only when you're above 35, and then a 30 mile per hour speed limit five feet ahead of that.

2618
03:17:42,853 --> 03:17:46,314
[SPEAKER_20]: And it's just, it's a mess right now and really, really dangerous.

2619
03:17:48,157 --> 03:17:51,820
[SPEAKER_20]: So I am glad that we're thinking about this.

2620
03:17:52,000 --> 03:18:03,109
[SPEAKER_20]: I think we need to go beyond painting, probably beyond another crosswalk, because getting cars to stop is the problem.

2621
03:18:04,471 --> 03:18:13,398
[SPEAKER_20]: And then finally, to tie it into some of the other conversations that have been going on tonight, I think if we're looking to limit parking at places of recreation,

2622
03:18:14,512 --> 03:18:21,157
[SPEAKER_20]: Right, Mystic River and the Fells, those are kind of the two gems of recreation within outdoor recreation in our community.

2623
03:18:22,178 --> 03:18:31,744
[SPEAKER_20]: We need to really make sure that if parking is limited, then the neighbors who live in those spaces can easily and safely access those places without a car.

2624
03:18:32,865 --> 03:18:34,887
[SPEAKER_20]: I think that really needs to happen.

2625
03:18:35,867 --> 03:18:43,793
[SPEAKER_20]: I purchased a car solely so I could safely get to Wright's Pond and the Fells, and it's like a mile away.

2626
03:18:44,359 --> 03:18:50,026
[SPEAKER_20]: I can get there easily, just not safely with my dog, my partner, all of those things.

2627
03:18:50,066 --> 03:18:53,409
[SPEAKER_20]: So I think that's a really important consideration.

2628
03:18:54,571 --> 03:18:54,811
[SPEAKER_20]: Thanks.

2629
03:18:55,492 --> 03:18:55,852
[SPEAKER_37]: Thank you.

2630
03:18:57,734 --> 03:19:01,078
[SPEAKER_37]: Any other questions or comments from the public?

2631
03:19:05,303 --> 03:19:05,423
[SPEAKER_37]: OK.

2632
03:19:07,559 --> 03:19:09,481
[SPEAKER_37]: Councilor Morales, I'd like to thank you for bringing this forward.

2633
03:19:09,521 --> 03:19:16,887
[SPEAKER_37]: As someone who lives up in this neighborhood, I think any type of public safety improvements that we can make up on Elm Street should be looked at.

2634
03:19:17,808 --> 03:19:27,375
[SPEAKER_37]: As the councilors have mentioned, I know since I've been on the city council, even before that, this has been an issue, but it's something that we need to make sure that we keep an eye on.

2635
03:19:27,475 --> 03:19:32,779
[SPEAKER_37]: And hopefully if we can work with the state, I know Representative Donato has been working on this for a while.

2636
03:19:35,359 --> 03:19:40,461
[SPEAKER_37]: Any public safety improvements that we can make in this area will benefit everyone.

2637
03:19:40,501 --> 03:19:41,561
[SPEAKER_37]: It can be very dangerous.

2638
03:19:41,601 --> 03:19:49,063
[SPEAKER_37]: That driveway going in and out of Wrights Pond is in a really difficult position because it's really a blind spot.

2639
03:19:49,823 --> 03:19:52,544
[SPEAKER_37]: But we need to make sure we keep it on the radar.

2640
03:19:52,584 --> 03:19:55,145
[SPEAKER_37]: We need to make sure that we, you know,

2641
03:19:55,717 --> 03:20:02,360
[SPEAKER_37]: really look at every possibility we can to make it safe for everyone to exit and enter the pond.

2642
03:20:02,440 --> 03:20:04,121
[SPEAKER_37]: So, thank you for bringing this forward.

2643
03:20:04,841 --> 03:20:11,664
[SPEAKER_37]: On the motion of Councilor Morrell, seconded by Councilor Behrs, as amended by Councilor Knight.

2644
03:20:12,284 --> 03:20:13,745
[SPEAKER_37]: Clerk, please call the roll.

2645
03:20:17,567 --> 03:20:18,187
[SPEAKER_57]: Councilor Behrs?

2646
03:20:19,107 --> 03:20:19,387
[SPEAKER_57]: Yes.

2647
03:20:20,208 --> 03:20:21,108
[SPEAKER_57]: Vice President Caravaglia?

2648
03:20:21,568 --> 03:20:21,828
[SPEAKER_57]: Yes.

2649
03:20:22,289 --> 03:20:22,749
[SPEAKER_57]: Councilor Knight?

2650
03:20:26,451 --> 03:20:26,751
[SPEAKER_57]: Yes.

2651
03:20:27,933 --> 03:20:28,834
[SPEAKER_57]: Thank you, Councilor Marks.

2652
03:20:29,415 --> 03:20:29,695
[SPEAKER_57]: Yes.

2653
03:20:30,436 --> 03:20:31,037
[SPEAKER_57]: Councilor Morrell.

2654
03:20:31,718 --> 03:20:31,978
[SPEAKER_57]: Yes.

2655
03:20:32,439 --> 03:20:33,200
[SPEAKER_57]: Councilor Scarpelli.

2656
03:20:34,382 --> 03:20:34,622
[SPEAKER_57]: Yes.

2657
03:20:35,123 --> 03:20:35,784
[SPEAKER_57]: President Falco.

2658
03:20:36,564 --> 03:20:39,426
[SPEAKER_37]: Yes, seven affirmative, zero in the negative, the motion passes.

2659
03:20:39,446 --> 03:20:55,757
[SPEAKER_37]: 20-497 offered by Council of Mayors, whereas systemic racism is an ongoing public health crisis that necessitates urgent action and whereas statements of solidarity and support can begin to address the history of racism and discrimination in our community.

2660
03:20:55,937 --> 03:21:06,304
[SPEAKER_37]: And whereas residents of Medford have requested that the city take this action now, therefore be resolved by the Medford City Council that the city of Medford will hang a banner reading Black Lives Matter

2661
03:21:06,684 --> 03:21:08,105
[SPEAKER_37]: on the front of Medford City Hall.

2662
03:21:08,305 --> 03:21:08,925
[SPEAKER_37]: Councilor Behrs.

2663
03:21:10,206 --> 03:21:11,087
[SPEAKER_29]: Thank you, Mr. President.

2664
03:21:11,587 --> 03:21:19,211
[SPEAKER_29]: I bring this resolution before the council today at the request of hundreds of residents who've asked that we hang a Black Lives Matter banner on Medford City Hall.

2665
03:21:20,072 --> 03:21:26,135
[SPEAKER_29]: This moment of uprising and reckoning with our history of white supremacy and racism demands it.

2666
03:21:26,795 --> 03:21:34,840
[SPEAKER_29]: As my fellow councilors and the public know, many communities have placed similar banners on schools, town halls, and other city buildings to show solidarity, respect, and support

2667
03:21:35,285 --> 03:21:40,848
[SPEAKER_29]: for the movement to address the ongoing structural racism that has been tearing families and communities apart in this country for centuries.

2668
03:21:41,748 --> 03:22:03,700
[SPEAKER_29]: We've seen protests and demonstrations for Black lives in our community, thousands of people standing up in person, online, through lawn signs and conversations to say no more, to say that we will not sweep this under the rug or treat this as a side issue when we know we can't move forward as a nation, as a community, or as a human family without permanent transformative change on the issues of structural racism and economic inequity.

2669
03:22:04,420 --> 03:22:06,902
[SPEAKER_29]: I expect we will have a robust discussion tonight.

2670
03:22:07,562 --> 03:22:14,528
[SPEAKER_29]: I hope it does not include any conspiracy theories that have been being forwarded around about this being some sort of fundraising front for the Democratic Party.

2671
03:22:15,268 --> 03:22:19,872
[SPEAKER_29]: And I also expect to hear the need to take action and not just say more words.

2672
03:22:19,912 --> 03:22:23,375
[SPEAKER_29]: And the assertion that this is about symbolism and not about substance.

2673
03:22:24,475 --> 03:22:31,581
[SPEAKER_29]: I would agree that it's about time that we dive deeply into charter review, rethinking how we elect elected officials in an all at large way.

2674
03:22:32,507 --> 03:22:37,371
[SPEAKER_29]: that diminishes racial representation and has been struck down by courts in other Massachusetts communities.

2675
03:22:38,111 --> 03:22:47,878
[SPEAKER_29]: I would agree that it's about time that we transform our city zoning and really root out the history of racial bias and zoning that permeated the zoning process when zoning was last reviewed in the city decades ago.

2676
03:22:48,839 --> 03:22:49,840
[SPEAKER_29]: Action is necessary.

2677
03:22:50,320 --> 03:22:55,003
[SPEAKER_29]: These are urgent projects on the path of transformation and they will take time, but words matter.

2678
03:22:55,884 --> 03:22:56,524
[SPEAKER_29]: Words matter.

2679
03:22:57,705 --> 03:22:58,646
[SPEAKER_29]: What we say matters.

2680
03:22:59,286 --> 03:23:01,248
[SPEAKER_29]: How we convey our support to the community matters.

2681
03:23:01,738 --> 03:23:05,962
[SPEAKER_29]: And I hope that by saying these words, we spur ourselves to take on the bigger things that we have to do as well.

2682
03:23:06,923 --> 03:23:21,678
[SPEAKER_29]: We know, and we've heard from Black parents and children and grandparents and brothers and sisters and neighbors and friends, from our neighbors and friends and residents of color, that this community has caused harm, that many have felt exclusion and disillusion and persecution in this community.

2683
03:23:22,499 --> 03:23:23,620
[SPEAKER_29]: I can never understand that.

2684
03:23:24,568 --> 03:23:35,870
[SPEAKER_29]: But when I try to even imagine the thousand stabs and paper cuts that our coworkers, neighbors, and friends of color experience on a daily basis, I can't begin to describe the horror that I feel.

2685
03:23:36,550 --> 03:23:51,353
[SPEAKER_29]: And I want every black parent, every child of color, every person in this community to know and to see when they walk by our city hall, the seat of power in this community, that we stand with them, that we hear them, that we will listen to them, talk to them,

2686
03:23:52,011 --> 03:23:56,212
[SPEAKER_29]: and empower them to lead this fight and fight alongside them, undaunted and undeterred.

2687
03:23:57,012 --> 03:24:13,297
[SPEAKER_29]: If my best friend experiences racist treatment, which I've seen over and over when we've been together, and then drives by our city hall, I want him to look up and see that we know that his life matters and that we are working to make that truly alive and real for everyone who calls Medford home.

2688
03:24:14,458 --> 03:24:15,638
[SPEAKER_29]: I wanna look up and know that.

2689
03:24:16,578 --> 03:24:18,739
[SPEAKER_29]: Mr. President, that's why I put forward this resolution

2690
03:24:19,246 --> 03:24:24,250
[SPEAKER_29]: why I and many others think this is a necessary and overdue step, and why I ask for my colleague's support.

2691
03:24:24,670 --> 03:24:24,990
[SPEAKER_29]: Thank you.

2692
03:24:26,051 --> 03:24:27,072
[SPEAKER_37]: Thank you, Councilor Behrs.

2693
03:24:28,272 --> 03:24:30,314
[SPEAKER_37]: Let's see, Councilor Morrell.

2694
03:24:31,555 --> 03:24:32,616
[SPEAKER_31]: Thank you, Mr. President.

2695
03:24:32,636 --> 03:24:35,037
[SPEAKER_31]: Yeah, I wanna thank Councilor Behrs for bringing this forward.

2696
03:24:35,097 --> 03:24:38,380
[SPEAKER_31]: I have a few comments on this if I could just read them off.

2697
03:24:39,400 --> 03:24:42,302
[SPEAKER_31]: So some people will say this is symbolism, and I definitely agree.

2698
03:24:42,583 --> 03:24:47,226
[SPEAKER_31]: It's symbolic of the commitments that we've made as a city, and this is the easy thing.

2699
03:24:47,728 --> 03:24:50,370
[SPEAKER_31]: If we can't do the easy thing, how will we do the hard work?

2700
03:24:50,890 --> 03:24:58,815
[SPEAKER_31]: How will we ensure that in 5, 10, 15, 25, 50 years, we're not right back here having done nothing of substance and learned nothing?

2701
03:24:59,535 --> 03:25:04,318
[SPEAKER_31]: So the uncomfortable truth is that for far too long, this country has said that Black lives do not matter.

2702
03:25:04,778 --> 03:25:11,002
[SPEAKER_31]: Their disparate health outcomes, their housing discrimination, and unequal rates of school suspension, arrests, and imprisonment.

2703
03:25:11,522 --> 03:25:12,583
[SPEAKER_31]: We say they do not matter.

2704
03:25:12,863 --> 03:25:17,366
[SPEAKER_31]: We said they do not matter by saying that all men are created equal, but in fact, not meaning Black men.

2705
03:25:18,188 --> 03:25:29,132
[SPEAKER_31]: So through chattel slavery, segregation, limiting voting rights, and Jim Crow, we have said that black lives do not matter, which is why we must now state unequivocally that black lives do matter.

2706
03:25:29,612 --> 03:25:31,513
[SPEAKER_31]: To say so is not a political act.

2707
03:25:31,853 --> 03:25:33,153
[SPEAKER_31]: It's a statement of human rights.

2708
03:25:34,073 --> 03:25:37,155
[SPEAKER_31]: We've declared systemic racism a public health crisis in this city.

2709
03:25:37,675 --> 03:25:44,577
[SPEAKER_31]: And perhaps if we have a reminder in front of city hall every day, we will make good on the work that is needed to actually address this crisis.

2710
03:25:45,057 --> 03:25:46,478
[SPEAKER_31]: And for this, I support this measure.

2711
03:25:46,778 --> 03:25:47,098
[SPEAKER_31]: Thank you.

2712
03:25:48,561 --> 03:25:49,421
[SPEAKER_31]: Thank you, Councilor Morrell.

2713
03:25:50,802 --> 03:25:53,363
[SPEAKER_37]: Any other questions or comments from the council?

2714
03:25:59,165 --> 03:26:00,465
[SPEAKER_37]: Okay, let's see.

2715
03:26:00,505 --> 03:26:07,568
[SPEAKER_37]: So on the motion of Councilor Behrs, I know a number of people have their hands up, but on the motion of Councilor Behrs, instead of a second.

2716
03:26:08,408 --> 03:26:09,329
[SPEAKER_41]: If I may, Mr. President.

2717
03:26:09,789 --> 03:26:10,229
[SPEAKER_41]: Councilor Lateef.

2718
03:26:13,271 --> 03:26:20,634
[SPEAKER_43]: Is there a policy in place that the administration abides by or goes by relative to the signing of the hanging of signs and banners on City Hall?

2719
03:26:22,775 --> 03:26:24,096
[SPEAKER_37]: I am not aware of one.

2720
03:26:25,977 --> 03:26:29,698
[SPEAKER_43]: I just, I support, you know, what Councilor Baez is saying.

2721
03:26:29,758 --> 03:26:31,139
[SPEAKER_43]: I say, you know, black lives do matter.

2722
03:26:31,359 --> 03:26:32,399
[SPEAKER_43]: I have no problem saying that.

2723
03:26:33,260 --> 03:26:38,242
[SPEAKER_43]: But I do have a concern when what happens when the next group comes down and says we want to hang our sign on City Hall too.

2724
03:26:43,280 --> 03:26:44,662
[SPEAKER_43]: What are the parameters?

2725
03:26:44,862 --> 03:26:45,523
[SPEAKER_43]: What are the guidelines?

2726
03:26:45,543 --> 03:26:48,266
[SPEAKER_43]: What are the criteria that the administration is going to put into play?

2727
03:26:48,867 --> 03:26:55,055
[SPEAKER_43]: Ultimately, we're not the body that's in charge or control of hanging anything on any city building.

2728
03:26:55,075 --> 03:26:56,016
[SPEAKER_43]: We're the legislative body.

2729
03:26:56,036 --> 03:26:57,378
[SPEAKER_43]: We're responsible for money and zoning.

2730
03:26:58,632 --> 03:26:59,392
[SPEAKER_43]: ordinances.

2731
03:26:59,812 --> 03:27:05,274
[SPEAKER_43]: So in looking at how this is going to play out and going forward, so what are we doing?

2732
03:27:05,294 --> 03:27:09,095
[SPEAKER_43]: We're telling the mayor, hang the sign, and the mayor's going to go, well, I have a policy that says I will.

2733
03:27:09,175 --> 03:27:10,295
[SPEAKER_43]: I have a policy that says I won't.

2734
03:27:10,435 --> 03:27:11,375
[SPEAKER_43]: There is no policy.

2735
03:27:11,435 --> 03:27:12,495
[SPEAKER_43]: We're working on a policy.

2736
03:27:13,076 --> 03:27:15,296
[SPEAKER_43]: I think it's important to know what the rules of the game are.

2737
03:27:20,397 --> 03:27:21,017
[SPEAKER_44]: Mr. President?

2738
03:27:23,518 --> 03:27:24,898
[SPEAKER_44]: Councilor Marks?

2739
03:27:26,339 --> 03:27:27,359
[SPEAKER_44]: Thank you, Mr. President.

2740
03:27:28,181 --> 03:27:30,522
[SPEAKER_44]: And I, too, have a statement tonight that I'd like to read.

2741
03:27:32,063 --> 03:27:38,187
[SPEAKER_44]: I first heard the phrase Black Lives Matter back in 2012, when Trayvon Martin was shot to death.

2742
03:27:39,287 --> 03:27:45,251
[SPEAKER_44]: After that, Michael Brown, a young African-American, was shot by a police officer in Ferguson, Missouri.

2743
03:27:46,331 --> 03:27:54,396
[SPEAKER_44]: Then another African-American, Eric Gander, died after being put in a chokehold by the New York City police officer.

2744
03:27:55,643 --> 03:28:15,431
[SPEAKER_44]: These incidences and many others leading up to George Floyd's murder this year have led me to understand how the seeds of slavery, discrimination, and prejudice continue to threaten the ability of black Americans and others to equally enjoy the freedoms that we profess as a country.

2745
03:28:16,596 --> 03:28:20,817
[SPEAKER_44]: So I am proud to join with so many others and state that black lives matter.

2746
03:28:21,857 --> 03:28:35,940
[SPEAKER_44]: I do so with the desire that in making this statement, it will facilitate the clear acknowledgement of the destructive effect that discrimination and prejudice has had and continues to have in our country.

2747
03:28:36,640 --> 03:28:42,641
[SPEAKER_44]: And my hope will encourage all Americans to work to erase inequality.

2748
03:28:43,746 --> 03:28:51,933
[SPEAKER_44]: But as we consider this resolution, I have an important question for the mayor about hanging banners on public buildings such as City Hall.

2749
03:28:53,094 --> 03:28:58,438
[SPEAKER_44]: My question is directed at the mayor because she has full authority over this building.

2750
03:28:59,499 --> 03:29:10,629
[SPEAKER_44]: My question is this, what standards or procedures does the mayor use in deciding what signs or messages will be placed on City Hall?

2751
03:29:11,892 --> 03:29:19,834
[SPEAKER_44]: The reason that I ask this question is because the right to use a government building to display a message is not unlimited.

2752
03:29:20,754 --> 03:29:25,535
[SPEAKER_44]: This is especially true if the building is a public forum like City Hall.

2753
03:29:26,815 --> 03:29:39,338
[SPEAKER_44]: If the mayor is going to allow City Hall to be used to display various messages, then the First Amendment requires that the city not discriminate among various messages or points of view.

2754
03:29:40,606 --> 03:29:45,288
[SPEAKER_44]: Any standard applied by the city must be content neutral.

2755
03:29:46,428 --> 03:29:51,309
[SPEAKER_44]: An example would be if a pro-life group wanted to hang a banner on City Hall.

2756
03:29:52,230 --> 03:29:59,152
[SPEAKER_44]: The city could not prohibit that, and nor could it prohibit a pro-choice group from also having its banner placed.

2757
03:30:00,032 --> 03:30:08,255
[SPEAKER_44]: So you can see that we should receive from the mayor a description of what the standards she applies in hanging banners.

2758
03:30:09,321 --> 03:30:19,317
[SPEAKER_44]: Otherwise, we could be at risk of turning City Hall building into a billboard battle zone of conflicting and possibly polarizing messages.

2759
03:30:20,433 --> 03:30:26,034
[SPEAKER_44]: In Method, we have experienced the impact that banners and signs have on our rights.

2760
03:30:27,014 --> 03:30:42,998
[SPEAKER_44]: It was just two years ago when this council voted to stop using the VFW building on Mystic Ave as a voting location because some voters stated they were less inclined to vote because of a sign displayed on the building.

2761
03:30:44,038 --> 03:30:48,699
[SPEAKER_44]: I mention this because City Hall itself is used as a voting location.

2762
03:30:49,741 --> 03:31:07,430
[SPEAKER_44]: So before we vote on a resolution, I am simply asking my council colleagues that we request that the mayor give us a full description of the standards or procedures she uses in determining what banners or signs will be allowed to be placed on City Hall.

2763
03:31:08,350 --> 03:31:16,094
[SPEAKER_44]: Having the mayor respond is a prudent and reasonable step to take when First Amendment and other rights are involved.

2764
03:31:17,113 --> 03:31:27,960
[SPEAKER_44]: So at this point, Mr. President, I would offer a motion to receive and place on file the original resolution of paper 20-497.

2765
03:31:28,880 --> 03:31:46,191
[SPEAKER_44]: And I offer a motion requesting that the mayor provide the council with the full description of the standards or procedures the mayor uses in determining what banners or signs will be allowed to be placed on City Hall.

2766
03:31:47,349 --> 03:31:47,729
[SPEAKER_44]: Thank you.

2767
