2810
03:35:33,305 --> 03:35:34,907
[SPEAKER_44]: District Court on July 1st, 2020.

2811
03:35:37,330 --> 03:35:41,732
[SPEAKER_44]: And it's the case of Judicial Watch versus the mayor of D.C.

2812
03:35:42,712 --> 03:35:49,815
[SPEAKER_44]: And on June 5th of this year, Mr. President, artists, demonstrators, residents, and employees of D.C.

2813
03:35:50,595 --> 03:35:54,816
[SPEAKER_44]: painted Black Lives Matter on 16th Street in Washington, D.C.

2814
03:35:55,917 --> 03:36:01,679
[SPEAKER_44]: The next day, June 6th, protesters painted Defund the Police next to Black Lives Matter.

2815
03:36:03,074 --> 03:36:11,083
[SPEAKER_44]: The mayor of DC, Muriel Bowser, supported the painting on the street, but there was no permit or approval process.

2816
03:36:12,364 --> 03:36:24,597
[SPEAKER_44]: Judicial Watch then wrote to Mayor Bowser and asked that their model, because no one is above the law, be painted on another street of the similar size.

2817
03:36:25,902 --> 03:36:39,315
[SPEAKER_44]: In its letter to the mayor, Judicial Watch said it has tried to find procedures for getting approval for painting a message on a street near its offices, but could not find any procedures or permit process.

2818
03:36:40,216 --> 03:36:45,402
[SPEAKER_44]: The deputy mayor then wrote back to Judicial Watch and said that it should apply for a permit.

2819
03:36:46,397 --> 03:36:54,408
[SPEAKER_44]: Judicial Watch then checked out the District of Columbia's website, but could not find a permit process to paint on a street.

2820
03:36:54,949 --> 03:37:00,377
[SPEAKER_44]: And when it contacted the Public Works Department, it was told, we never heard of that permit.

2821
03:37:01,274 --> 03:37:06,880
[SPEAKER_44]: Judicial Watch then entered the lawsuit alleging a violation of its First Amendment rights.

2822
03:37:07,520 --> 03:37:17,311
[SPEAKER_44]: The basis for its claim is the mayor favors one message over another, and that the city does not have any standards or procedures in place.

2823
03:37:18,450 --> 03:37:32,620
[SPEAKER_44]: So I just want to make it be known, Mr. President, I think it's prudent that this council move forward to find out what are the standards and what are the procedures, Mr. President, because clearly anything could be challenged.

2824
03:37:33,060 --> 03:37:42,726
[SPEAKER_44]: And clearly that if we do open up messaging on City Hall, it will open up other First Amendment rights and other concerns.

2825
03:37:43,167 --> 03:37:46,549
[SPEAKER_44]: And I think it's only prudent that we move forward as a community

2826
